comments:
That's a great point! Unfortunately Topological Sort generates a linear order, forcing nodes to run one after another. This library attempts to bring some parallel processing into the picture by grouping dependence-free nodes together.  This produces a linear batches.  {C D E F}, {parentA parentB}, {root} 

Within a batch, nodes can run parallel.  Between batches, they still need to run one after another.What you're asking for is to partition the dependency graph according to node dependency with minimum span.  { {C D} parentA } \
  { {E F} parentB } - {root}

Or with a shared dependence.  { {C D S} parentA } \
  { {E F S} parentB } - {root}

And on top of that, add node weight into the consideration.  That's hard.For now, you can send notification to a dependent when the leading task finishes.  E.g. When C finishes, notifies parentA.  When D finishes, notifies parentA.  When parentA notices that all its leading tasks have done, it can start.The library can help in maintaining the dependency relationship and let the task query its leaders and dependents.

